{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"The number of malaria-positive cases dropped sharply in mid-2024, with volumes ~25–32% below expected in March–April and remaining depressed through much of the year. By 2025, detected cases rose again, returning closer to expected levels by June (~2% below trend).

ACT treatment closely followed the trend in positive cases, with marked declines in 2024 and higher volumes in 2025. By June 2025, treatment levels remained somewhat close to expected, and the close alignment with positive cases indicates that most detected cases continued to be treated.

Malaria typically rises during the rainy season, but timing and peak sharpness vary by district. The model captures seasonality at the national level, but does not fully reflect these local differences."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"6dabd0e2-b4c1-46a6-890e-62007b79eac3","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Malaria-positive cases and treatment fell in 2023–24, with increased detection in 2025"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"After tracking near expected early in 2025, BCG rose above trend in Q2. From April–June, surpluses of 9–11% were recorded, with June reaching ~25,600 doses, reflecting stronger and sustained newborn vaccination at birth.

Penta1 volumes stayed close to expected through 2025, with only minor deviations. In June, ~28,900 doses (~7% above expected) reflected stable alignment with trend rather than a major surplus. Strengthening this early dose remains key for continuity of the series.

Penta3 volumes mostly tracked expectations but surged in late 2024 (+11–15%) and April 2025 (+14%), likely from catch-up or campaigns. By June, ~26,500 doses (~4% above expected) signaled a return to stable trend."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"fb3f7d80-0796-46ae-9009-350bb33a615a","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Immunization services strengthen in 2025, with gains in BCG and Penta3"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Short-acting FP methods experienced repeated disruptions: a major shortfall in mid-2024 (21–24% below expected), another dip in Dec 2024 (~18% below), and early 2025 (~15% below). A brief rebound occurred in Mar 2025, when volumes rose ~12% above expected.

Long-acting FP methods remained largely within expected ranges in 2025, with no consistent disruptions flagged, though pre-2024 variability may reflect reporting completeness issues.

Overall, FP services remain unstable, with short-acting methods driving most of the recent disruptions."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"d6e68d9a-0b2b-46ee-921a-f55833d762f4","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Family planning service use remains unstable, with repeated disruptions in short-acting methods through 2024–25 despite brief periods of recovery"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"image","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgFile":"26372818523_c88eeb2825_o.jpg","imgFit":"cover","markdown":"","imgStretch":true,"imgHeight":250},{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"primary","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"markdown":"The FASTR approach uses routine HMIS data to monitor how service delivery shifts over time.

By comparing observed vs. expected service volumes — adjusted for seasonality and historical trends — we can identify disruptions or surpluses in key health services.

This analysis provides a timely, system-wide perspective, highlighting where and when service use deviates from expected patterns. Findings generate actionable evidence to guide rapid responses, helping sustain continuity of essential care during funding uncertainty or operational change."}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Tracking Disruptions in Essential Services Using HMIS Data","useFooter":false,"footerLogos":[]}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"ANC1 visits were consistently above expectations in 2025, averaging ~26,900 per month vs. ~24,200 expected (~11% higher), with June 2025 ~26,200 visits (~9% above expected).

ANC4 visits stayed close to expected levels, averaging ~19,300 per month vs. ~18,800 expected (~3% higher), with June 2025 ~18,900 visits (~5% above expected).

Both indicators align with expected trends, though ANC1 shows clearer gains. Continuity remains a concern, as fewer women complete ANC4 compared to ANC1."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"b32538b0-928a-466c-95b1-6ff2ebbff03c","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"ANC1 shows slight surpluses in 2025, while ANC4 stays near trend, but continuity gap remains"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"In 2025, deliveries rose steadily above expected levels, reaching ~14% higher than trend by June. This shows stronger uptake of facility-based births — a key entry point for maternal–newborn care.

Newborn PNC visits rose to ~8% above expected by June 2025, but gains are smaller than for deliveries. While gains are smaller than for deliveries, volumes still reached about 90% of delivery levels, suggesting some newborns are not receiving timely follow-up after birth.

Maternal PNC visits climbed to ~9% above expected by June 2025. PNC for mothers reached about 93% of delivery levels, pointing to modest but persistent gaps in linking facility births with postpartum care."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"2ff8805a-0463-464f-84e3-36c6dae098b8","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Institutional deliveries and PNC visits rise above expected levels in 2025, but continuity of care gap remains"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Since mid-2023, BCG vaccination volumes have averaged about 10 % below expected levels, reflecting a sustained but moderate shortfall in newborn immunization coverage that gradually stabilized within expected ranges by mid-2025.

Penta 1 and Penta 3 remained within expected levels, with monthly differences ranging from about –3 % to +3 %.
"},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"cf3b04ed-e85d-4eda-bdc5-6575b0240821","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Slight disruptions for BCG, followed by recovery to expected levels in June 2025"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","span":3,"markdown":"In 2025, the largest ANC1 volume occurred in January, with approximately 90,000 visits. For ANC4, the highest volume was observed in April 2025, at nearly 80,000 visits.

On average, ANC4 volumes are about 10,000 visits lower than ANC1 — indicating that roughly 10–12% fewer women progress to their fourth antenatal visit compared to the first.

